	     Johannesburg – President Jacob Zuma on Thursday appointed 15 individuals to serve as judges in High Courts across the country. This after receiving advice on suitable candidates from the Judicial Service Commission. Zuma wished them all the best with their new responsibilities. Here is a list of the appointed judges: - Justice Selby Mfanelo Mbenenge as Judge President of the Eastern Cape Division of the High Court, with effect from November 7, 2017. - Ndumiso Patrick Jaji as Judge of the Eastern Cape Division of the High Court, Grahamstown, with effect from November 1, 2017. - Mbulelo Stanford Jolwana as a Judge of the Eastern Cape Local Division of the High Court, Mthatha, with effect from November 1, 2017. - Advocate Philip Jacobus Loubser SC as a Judge of the Free State Division of the High Court, Bloemfontein, with effect from December 16, 2017. - Colleen Jane Collis as a Judge of the Gauteng Division of the High Court, with effect from January 1, 2018. - Advocate Norman Davis SC as a Judge of the Gauteng Division of the High Court, with effect from 1 January 1, 2018. - Maletsatsi Betty Mahalelo as a Judge of the Gauteng Division of the High Court, with effect from January 1, 2018. - Advocate Tintswalo Annah Nana Makhubele SC as a Judge of the Gauteng Division of the High Court, with effect from January 1, 2018. - Cassim Mohamed Sardiwalla as a Judge of the Gauteng Division of the High Court, with effect from January 1, 2018. - Advocate Cornelius Jacobus van der Westhuizen SC as a Judge of the Gauteng Division of the High Court, with effect from January 1, 2018. - Taswell Deverill Papier as a Judge of the Western Cape Division of the High Court, Cape Town, with effect from November 1, 2017. - Mushtak Kassim Parker as a Judge of the Western Cape Division of the High Court, Cape Town, with effect from November 1, 2017. - Advocate Mark Louis Sher SC as a Judge of the Western Cape Division of the High Court, Cape Town, with effect from November 1, 2017. - Eduard Derek Wille as a Judge of the Western Cape Division of the High Court, Cape Town, with effect from November 1, 2017.  24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.  